@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction - About FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

FlashPlayer is a player for Macromedia's (now Adobe's) "flash" interactive
animation format, also known as SWF. The flash format was originally
invented as a very bandwidth-efficient means for delivering animation
across the Internet. It has since grown into an interactive presentation
format, complete with its own scripting language.

Like all flash animation players for the Amiga, FlashPlayer is based on
the open-source @{"swf library" link "Credits" 23} by Olivier Debon. FlashPlayer has made many
improvements to the original swf library, and has wrapped around it a
full-featured GUI. However, despite the improvements, FlashPlayer still
suffers many of the limitations of the swf library, including limited or
missing support for many of the newer additions to the flash format.

This documentation is for the standalone version of FlashPlayer. The stand-
alone version is capable of playing flash animations without the use of any
other program. FlashPlayer is also available separately as an IBrowse
plugin, which allows flash animations to be viewed as part of a web page.
The plugin of course requires IBrowse.

@{b}Features:@{ub}

o @{i}Fairly complete support for Flash 1 through Flash 3 formats @{ui}

  Most of these older animations will play pretty much as intended.

o @{i}Limited support for Flash 4 and up @{ui}

  Does not support scripting, so while it will not malfunction when
  presented with a newer animation, it may not play it as intended. Newer
  animations may play just fine, however, if they don't use any of the
  unsupported features (I've seen Flash 8 and Flash 9 animations that work
  fine with FlashPlayer).

o @{i}Uses @{"render.library and guigfx.library" link "Credits" 79} for best image quality @{ui}

  Can play flash animations on any screen, from two color low-res OCS to
  24-bit graphics cards. Supports OCS, ECS, AGA, CyberGraphics, and Picasso
  96. Uses dithering for improved display quality on color-mapped screens.

o @{i}Public and custom screen support @{ui}

  Can open on the Workbench or on a web browser's screen, or can open its
  own screen, in any resolution or format.

o @{i}Uses @{"AHI" link "Credits" 85} for flexible audio output @{ui}

  Plays sound on any hardware for which AHI has a driver. Supports 16-bit
  audio.

o @{i}Uses @{"openurl.library" link "Credits" 90} for web browser support @{ui}

  Allows any supported browser to visit web pages linked to by a flash
  animation. (The plugin offers even better support for IBrowse users.)

o @{i}Built-in decoding of MP3 sounds @{ui}

  Contains an integrated version of the open-source @{"MAD MP3 decoder" link "Credits" 45}; does
  not require mpega.library or other external decoder.

o @{i}Support for alternate hardware platforms @{ui}

  Because it does not depend on native Amiga hardware for graphics or
  sound, FlashPlayer works with Amiga emulators and with the latest Amiga
  hardware (it has been ported to MorphOS with minimal effort, and runs
  under emulation on UAE and the AmigaOne).

o @{i}Runs from @{"Workbench" link "Workbench" 0} or @{"shell" link "Shell" 0} @{ui}

  Can be run in any of the normal ways, including via the WB 3.5+ default
  icon system, and as a MIME-driven player for a web browser. Reads program
  arguments from its own icon (even if run from the shell), and from icons
  for the files it's playing. If run on the Workbench screen, files can be
  played by dropping them on the FlashPlayer window.

o @{i}@{"Menu and keyboard control" link "Control" 0} of the flash animation @{ui}

  Stop, start, frame advance, and rewind the animation. Zoom in on the
  animation, and scroll around within the zoomed-in frame.

o @{i}Configurable, for maximum flexibility @{ui}

  Uses @{"tooltypes or command-line arguments" link "Options" 0} to set the screen type, the
  playback quality, the size and scale (enlarged or reduced) of the
  animation, enable or disable sound, streaming sound, looping, and URL
  support, adjust the sound buffer size, and set the diagnostic output
  level.

o @{i}Selectable diagnostic output @{ui}

  Can be set to generate no diagnostic output, output only on errors, or
  to trace its operation, which can be helpful in understanding why a
  particular animation is not playing as expected. Diagnostic output
  appears in a separate console window.

@{b}Limitations:@{ub}

o @{i}Does not support many of the newer additions to the flash format @{ui}

  Chief among these is the scripting language first added to Flash 4, and
  extended in newer flash versions. Some animations depend on scripting and
  will not run without it, while others use it only as an enhancement, and
  can still be viewed to some extent even without scripting support.

o @{i}Resource-intensive @{ui}

  While the flash files themselves can be small, decoding and presenting
  them requires lots of memory and lots of processor cycles (a reflection
  of the origins of the flash format and of the swf presentation engine on
  the PC platform). A fairly high-end system is required to play any but
  the smallest and simplest animations, and even a 68060 is unable to play
  most animations at their intended speed (or to play streaming sound
  without dropouts).

o @{i}Only plays one animation at a time @{ui}

  FlashPlayer will only play a single animation; if you want to play more
  than one at a time, you will need to run the program again. It would be
  more memory-efficient to allow the program to play multiple animations,
  though it's slow enough that this is not likely something you'll want to
  do very much of.

o @{i}No PowerPC version @{ui}

  There is no PPC version of FlashPlayer because I don't have a PPC system
  to develop it on. The @{"source code" link "Credits" 11} is available, if anyone wants to port
  it to the PPC. A successful port to MorphOS has been performed, and
  FlashPlayer runs under emulation on AmigaOS 4 and WinUAE.

o @{i}Problems with CD-ROMs @{ui}

  FlashPlayer cannot open a flash movie located on a CD-ROM when using
  AsimCDFS as the CD filesystem, because AsimCDFS does not implement the
  DOS function OpenFromLock(), which FlashPlayer uses. Other CD-ROM
  filesystems may work better.

@endnode

@node "Varieties" "Varieties of FlashPlayer"

@{b}@{fg shine}Varieties of FlashPlayer - The standalone player vs. the plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

Starting with version 1.5, there are two varieties of FlashPlayer- a
standalone player, and an IBrowse plugin. Each is available separately,
and each has its uses.

Most flash content is found on the web, and the most common way to view it
is with a web browser. This allows the animations to be integrated into the
web page in a manner that cannot easily be duplicated with a standalone
player. The IBrowse plugin version of FlashPlayer is obviously best suited
to this use.

However, the standalone version of FlashPlayer also has uses. There are
times when it may be desirable to view an animation without having the
overhead of a web browser present. The standalone player also allows more
control over the presentation of the animation than does the plugin.

It's also easy to set up an icon for a flash file to run the standalone
player when it is double-clicked, and the tooltypes in the icon can be
customized to present that particular animation optimally.

Of course, not everyone uses IBrowse as their web browser, and so may not
be able to use the FlashPlayer plugin. Voyager has a flash plugin of its
own, though it's not nearly as powerful as FlashPlayer. As far as I know,
AWeb has no flash plugin. Users of both of these browsers may still find
the standalone version of FlashPlayer useful to view online flash content.

And finally, it's simply easier for me to test new FlashPlayer features
using the standalone player, without needing to bring IBrowse into the
equation.

The standalone version of FlashPlayer continues to support openurl.ibrary,
and will try to pass URLs linked to by an animation to a browser to be
opened. For links that don't contain the full path to the target, Flash-
Player will try to load the file from the local drive, allowing some
animations to load others without requiring the assistance of a browser.

The standalone FlashPlayer filters out URLs of the form "FSCommand:", which
are intended to control a flash player plugin, and which are meaningless to
the browser. URLs of the form "Javascript:" will be passed to the browser.
These may or may not work, depending on what the Javascript command is
trying to do. Simple commands to open or close windows and the like will
likely succeed. Complex commands often won't.

@endnode

@node "Credits" "Credits"

@{b}@{fg shine}Credits - Who is behind FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

FlashPlayer is freely distributable, open-source software, copyright ©
2004 - 2009 by Mike Steed. It is distributed WITHOUT WARRANTY, under the
terms of the @{"GNU General Public License (GPL)" link "COPYING/main" 0}. See the license for
details.

As an open-source project, FlashPlayer depends on the work of many
programmers:

o The Amiga-specific and user interface portions of the program were
  written by Mike Steed @{b}(72207.463@compuserve.com)@{ub}. Source code for
  FlashPlayer (both the standalone and plugin versions) is available on
  Aminet at @{b}www.aminet.net/gfx/show/FlashPlayerSrc.lha@{ub}.

o Help in developing the IBrowse plugin version of FlashPlayer was provided
  by the IBrowse developers, in particular Oliver Roberts. The sample flash
  plugin provided by the IBrowse team was helpful in figuring out the
  IBrowse plugin API. The Netscape plugin API documentation and reference
  code was also helpful, since the IBrowse plugin API is based on the
  NPAPI.

o The flash format file decoding and presentation engine and the low-level
  graphics rendering and sound mixing portions of the program are via the
  swf library by Olivier Debon. Source to the original version of this
  library (version 0.4.10) is available at @{b}www.swift-tools.net/Flash@{ub}. The
  original library has been modified for Amiga compatibility and enhanced
  to add new features and to fix bugs by Mike Steed. Source to the modified
  library (version 0.5.6) is available as part of the FlashPlayer source.

o Many of the improvements to the swf library made during the development
  of FlashPlayer have also been incorporated into the GplFlash project, the
  "official" continuation of Olivier Debon's original work. GplFlash is
  available at @{b}sourceforge.net/projects/gplflash@{ub}.

o The swf library uses the libjpeg JPEG encoder/decoder library version 6b
  by the Independent JPEG Group, to decode the JPEG images found in flash
  files. Source to this library is available at @{b}www.ijg.org@{ub}.

o The swf library uses the zlib compression/decompression library version
  1.2.3 by Jean-loup Gailly and Mark Adler, to decode the zlib-compressed
  images found in flash files, and to decode compressed flash files.
  Source to this library is available at @{b}www.zlib.net@{ub}.

o Mike Steed's enhanced version of the swf library uses the libmad MPEG
  audio decoder library version 0.15.1b by Underbit Technologies, Inc, to
  decode MP3 audio found in flash files. Source to this library may be
  found at @{b}www.underbit.com/products/mad@{ub}.

o The embedded font found in the swf library of FlashPlayer v. 1.6 and
  later is NimbusSanL-Regu, from the Ghostscript font collection. It was
  converted to swf format by font2swf from the swftools suite, and was
  further massaged to reduce the amount of space required to store it.
  Source data for the processed font is part of the FlashPlayer source.

o FlashPlayer was inspired by the port of the swf library to the Amiga done
  by Paul Hill, and the player he wrote to utilize it (SwfPlayer version
  1.1). Both were formerly available at @{b}www.lagernet.clara.co.uk/@{ub}
  @{b}swfplayer.html@{ub}, but that site now seems to be offline. A bit of code
  from Paul's version made it into FlashPlayer as well.

o Further inspiration, testing under OS4, and collaboration on adding new
  feaures to the swf library came from Alexandre Balaban and his SwfPlayer
  version 1.2 and above, available on Aminet and at
  @{b}http://abalaban.free.fr/swfplayer.html@{ub}. Alexandre is also administrator
  of the GplFlash project.

o Beta testing and many example swf files were provided by Todd Oberly, who
  has an invaluable knack for finding files that make FlashPlayer fail in
  interesting ways. Many of the bug fixes were inspired by problems he
  found.

o Maxim Ilyin and Alex Ivanov ported FlashPlayer to MorphOS (available on
  Aminet), and also contributed the code to load Flash EXE files.

As an Amiga program, FlashPlayer depends on a number of third-party shared
libraries for its operation:

o guigfx.library and render.library by Timm S. Müller / neoscientists are
  used to render the 24-bit output of the swf library's presentation engine
  to an Amiga screen. These libraries are included with FlashPlayer, and
  are also available on Aminet and at @{b}http://users.neoscientists.org/@{ub}
  @{b}~bifat/binarydistillery@{ub}.

o AHI by Martin Blom is used to play sounds generated by the swf library
  via either the Amiga's built-in audio output, or via a sound card. AHI is
  included with OS 3.5 and 3.9, and is also available on Aminet and at
  @{b}www.lysator.liu.se/ahi@{ub}.

o openurl.library, originally by Troels Walsted Hansen, and now maintained
  by the openurl.library Open Source Team is used to allow FlashPlayer to
  pass URLs generated by the swf library to a web browser. openurl.library
  may be found on Aminet and at @{b}sourceforge.net/projects/openurllib@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements - What is required to run FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

FlashPlayer needs at least the following in order to run at all:

 o AmigaOS 3.0
 o 68020 processor with FPU
 o @{"guigfx.library and render.library" link "Credits" 79} (both included with the program)
 o Several MB of available RAM (beyond what the OS requires)

The minimum system above will play small animations slowly, but is
underpowered for serious use. A more practical system includes the
following:

 o AmigaOS 3.1 or newer
 o 68040 or 68060 processor with FPU
 o A graphics card (Zorro 3 or local bus is best)
 o @{"guigfx.library and render.library" link "Credits" 79}
 o @{"AHI" link "Credits" 85} (version 4 or newer)
 o A web browser (most flash files are found on the web)
 o @{"openurl.library" link "Credits" 90} (version 1 or newer)
 o Five to 10 MB of available RAM (beyond that used by the OS and browser)

FlashPlayer is compiled for a 68040, but will run on any processor from the
68020 through the 68060. For speed, the code requires that a hardware FPU
(either built-in or external) be present.

FlashPlayer is not available in a Power PC version, since I have no PPC on
which to develop it. It has been reported to run under emulation on AmigaOS
4 and WinUAE. A MorphOS native version is also available.

@endnode

@node "History" "Version History"

@{b}@{fg shine}Version History - The evolution of FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}Version 1.6 12-Oct-09 (posted to Aminet 30-Oct-09)@{ub}

I started to look at adding Flash 4 scripting to FlashPlayer, but realized
that a few features were still missing that would be necessary to support
scripting. Since these features were also useful without scripting, I went
ahead and added them to this version, instead of having to wait longer for
a version that includes scripting. Along the way I also tackled some long-
standing bugs.

Features added:

o Added partial support for edit text fields. Actual editing of text
  requires scripting, and so is not supported. However, edit text fields
  are often used to hold static ("read-only") text, and this text will be
  displayed.

  There are a number of limitations to the display of edit text. HTML-
  encoded text is displayed as plain text, with the HTML formatting
  removed. Scrolling of text is not supported, so text that is too large
  to fit will be clipped. Scripts may change the contents of an edit text
  field under script control; with no support for scripting, FlashPlayer
  cannot display this dynamic text.

  Despite these limitations, the ability to display edit text fields allows
  quite a bit of text that was formerly invisible to be seen, even though
  it may not look exactly as intended.

o Added partial support for device fonts, which are frequently used with
  edit text fields. Device fonts use platform-native fonts to display text,
  instead of swf fonts that are built into the animation. It would be diff-
  icult to support device fonts in a platform-independent fashion, so the
  swf library that FlashPlayer uses substitutes a built-in swf font in
  place of the platform-native font.

  To keep the size of the program down, there is only a single built-in
  font, which is used regardless of which device font the animation is
  requesting. Most animations that use device fonts request some variety of
  sans-serif font such as Arial or Helvetica, so for best compatibility the
  built-in font is a sans-serif font.

o The new JPEG image type added to Flash 10 files will be displayed, though
  without the deblocking filter associated with the image.

Improvements made:

o Button handling has been improved. FlashPlayer now recognizes the
  difference between menu buttons and push buttons, as defined by the Flash
  file format specification (previously all buttons were treated as menu
  buttons).

  Push buttons "capture" the mouse, so the button will remain active if the
  mouse is moved off of the button while held down. Any actions triggered
  by this activity will occur, rather than being ignored.

  If a button release sound is present it will be played; previously it was
  ignored. Some buttons that have an action associated with the release of
  the button will now have that action performed at the proper time;
  previously the action occurred when the button was pressed, instead.

o The swf library used by FlashPlayer now refreshes the display properly
  when zooming and scrolling an animation using the numeric keypad, making
  this feature usable at last.

o The swf library now recognizes all actions and tags found in Flash files
  up through version 10. Of course, it still doesn't understand most of the
  newer ones, but it will list them when an animation is loaded with the
  output set to verbose. Actions and tags that are unsupported by Flash-
  Player are listed as such.

o Enhanced the amount of information output when loading an animation if
  the output is set to verbose. In particular, a lot more information about
  scripts is generated. This is mainly for my benefit when doing develop-
  ment work on the library, but might be interesting to curious users as
  well.

o The new v. 7 of the JPEG decoder library used by the swf library was
  tested, but it's both larger and slower than v. 6b, while not offering
  any new features that are useful to FlashPlayer. So FlashPlayer continues
  to use the older version.

Bugs fixed:

o The highlighting of buttons that have been selected via the keyboard was
  almost totally broken in earlier versions of the swf library, making key-
  board operation of buttons nearly impossible. These bugs have all been
  fixed, so that @{"keyboard operation" link "Control" 63} actually works now.

o One of the above-mentioned bugs caused memory corruption and possibly a
  crash when trying to draw a highlight box around a selected button; this
  code now works correctly.

o Parsing of "dangerous" actions such as script branches was not aborted
  properly when the actions were attached to a button, sometimes causing
  other actions attached to the button to not be executed properly, even
  if they weren't "dangerous".


@{b}Version 1.5 26-Dec-08 (posted to Aminet 30-Dec-08)@{ub}

The bulk of the effort in FlashPlayer 1.5 went into creating the IBrowse
plugin. But I did find time to add some new features to the standalone
player, as well as to fix a few bugs.

Features added:

o Now that Adobe has made the Flash 9 specification freely available, at
  least partial support for some of the new Flash 8 and Flash 9 features
  has been added.

  The new high-resolution font format added to Flash 8 is now supported,
  though FlashPlayer doesn't contain the new high-quality font rendering
  engine, and so displays these fonts at the same resolution and quality
  as the older ones.

  FlashPlayer will also draw the new shapes and morphing shapes added to
  Flash 8. For speed reasons it does not support most of the new features
  of those shapes (such as run-time filter effects, focal gradients, and
  selectable line cap and join styles), so while the shapes will appear,
  they might not look like entirely like they were intended to.

  The swf library now recognizes all actions and tags found in Flash files
  up through version 9. Of course, it still doesn't understand many of the
  newer ones, but it will list them when an animation is loaded with the
  output set to verbose. Actions and tags that are unsupported by Flash-
  Player are listed as such.

  FlashPlayer still sometimes reports unknown tags. These are either pro-
  prietary tags inserted by flash authoring tools, or tags that are un-
  documented by Adobe.

Improvements made:

o Optimized the swf library used by FlashPlayer to mix colors more
  efficiently when rendering an animation, leading to a significant
  speedup.

o Diagnostic output is now written using Amiga library routines, rather
  than the compiler's file writing routines. This removes a couple of
  Kbytes of code, making FlashPlayer a little smaller.

o The term "(unsupported)" is used a lot in the diagnostic output. The
  code has been optimized so that the term is only stored once, and that
  single instance is used by all of the diagnostic output. This reduces
  the size of the program by another 1.5 Kbytes.

o Animations with only a single frame no longer loop, even if looping is
  enabled. These animations typically use sprites embedded within the
  single frame for their action, and looping prevented the sprites from
  running. This reduces the number of animations that don't play correctly
  when looping is enabled, and has allowed looping to be enabled rather
  than disabled by default.

Bugs fixed:

o Fixed bugs in the swf library that caused the rightmost column and bottom
  line of pixels in the animation to not be drawn. This was difficult to
  see in the standalone player due to the proximity of the missing lines to
  the window borders, but was quite apparent in the plugin.

o The swf library would crash when loading a broken animation that had more
  frames than it declared it had. The library will now ignore any frames
  beyond the number declared.

o The swf library would crash or cause Enforcer hits when trying to render
  very long lines, such as a shape that's been magnified until only a
  small portion of it is visible in the window. Clipping is now performed
  to prevent this.

o FlashPlayer wasn't closing AHI properly when quit- it didn't specifically
  stop any sounds that were still playing, and it freed the sound buffers
  while AHI was still using them. Oddly, in the standalone player this
  didn't seem to cause any problems. It caused the plugin to crash however,
  so it was fixed for both the plugin and the standalone player.

o The improved color reduction that was added to FlashPlayer v. 1.4 when
  processing lossless-compressed bitmap images did not correctly handle
  24-bit images without an alpha channel, displaying random garbage instead
  of the image. It now handles these images correctly.

o The default sound buffer size was supposed to have been increased to 96K
  back in v. 1.2, but it was in fact still set to 64K.


@{b}Version 1.4 22-Dec-07 (posted to Aminet 26-Dec-07)@{ub}

This version of FlashPlayer was to be a quick release, to hold users over
during the development of the plugin version. But getting morphing shapes
to work took much more time that I'd thought, resulting in a version with
fewer new features than I would have liked, considering the development
time.

Features added:

o Morphing shapes are now displayed, rather than being ignored as in
  earlier versions of FlashPlayer. The rendering of morphing shapes is
  rather complex, and real-world morphing shapes don't always work like
  the flash format specification says. Because of this, FlashPlayer may
  not always render a morphing shape 100% correctly.

  Rendering of morphing shapes is a little slower than that of regular
  shapes, due to the morphing process. And of course, it takes more time
  to draw a shape than to ignore it, which is what earlier versions of
  FlashPlayer did. Because of this, animations with morphing shapes will
  play more slowly with FlashPlayer 1.4 than with earlier versions.
  Animations without morphing shapes are unaffected.

Improvements made:

o Sprites (small animations within the main animation) may now be used as
  mask objects. Previously they were ignored, causing the objects they were
  supposed to mask to be invisible. There are limitations, however- if the
  sprite being used as a mask has a mask of its own, that mask will be
  ignored.

o Added an internal memory pool system to the swf library used by Flash-
  Player, greatly reducing the number of system memory allocations and
  frees that the player performs while playing an animation. This makes for
  a significant speed increase when playing animations with large, complex
  shapes (which includes many morphing shapes), or with a large number of
  simpler shapes. It also reduces memory usage and fragmentation.

o The swf library used by FlashPlayer converts all bitmap images to color-
  mapped (8 bit) form for its internal use. For JPEG images it uses sophis-
  ticated color reduction techniques, including dithering, to maintain the
  image quality. For lossless-compressed images, however, it performed the
  color reduction very simply. Since most lossless-compressed images are
  illustrations with few colors and little subtle or realistic shading,
  this actually worked pretty well. But the occasional photographic image
  looked quite poor.

  The swf library has been enhanced to perform more sophisticated color
  reduction on these images (though still not as good as for JPEG images).
  This doesn't make much difference for most lossless-compressed images,
  but the occasional photographic image looks much better.

o The swf library more completely rewinds an animation when the "Rewind"
  menu item is chosen.

Bugs fixed:

o During pre-release testing of version 1.3, the code that makes sure that
  FlashPlayer's stack is at least 10 Kbytes was removed, and never
  restored. If run with a stack less than about 8 Kbytes, FlashPlayer might
  overflow its stack and crash. Sorry about that.

o The swf library used by FlashPlayer was ignoring the alpha (transparency)
  data included with 24-bit lossless-compressed bitmap images, causing
  those images to be drawn without transparency. This affected many
  animations, typically causing a black box to appear around the image.
  This was very obvious in some animations, and more subtle in others.
  They all should play correctly now.

o Fixed some possible crashes or memory leaks caused by the swf library
  under error conditions (typically, when runing low on memory).


@{b}Version 1.3 02-Nov-06 (posted to Aminet 08-Nov-06)@{ub}

Other obligations prevented me from getting as much work done on this
version as I'd hoped, but I was still able to add some significant new
features.

Features added:

o FlashPlayer can now load and play additional animations within the first,
  allowing for "picture in picture" functionality. Unfortunately, this new
  ability is severely limited by the fact that FlashPlayer is not a real
  browser plugin.

  The problem is that FlashPlayer has no way to tell the browser to load
  the second animation and make it available to the player. So the ani-
  mation ends up in a second FlashPlayer window, instead of as a part of
  the first. This limitation can't be fixed until FlashPlayer becomes a
  real plugin.

  When told by an animation being played to load another animation,
  FlashPlayer will first try to load the new animation from the same
  directory of the local drive in which the first animation is located.
  Only if this does not succeed will it try to load the animation using
  the browser. This allows such animations to be viewed offline, as long
  as all of the animations are present on the local drive.

o FlashPlayer can now load executable flash files (Flash EXEs), which
  include a built-in version of the Windows flash player along with the
  actual SWF file. FlashPlayer will locate the embedded SWF file, while
  ignoring the built-in player. The technique that FlashPlayer uses to
  locate the SWF file works with EXE files containing the official Flash 5
  and Flash 6 players, but hasn't been tested with other types of Flash
  EXE file.

o The swf library now supports masked rendering, which allows invisible
  "mask objects" to mask portions of the animation which are behind and
  outside the borders of the mask object. Masking is used fairly exten-
  sively by flash animations for special effects such as rainbow-colored
  text, and also to help add "depth" to the animation.

  The addition of masked rendering does not affect the speed of animations
  that don't use masks, and only slows animations that have simple or
  small masks slightly. But animations that make extensive use of masking
  inevitably run slower than with earlier versions of FlashPlayer, as it
  is now paying attention to something that was formerly ignored.

  A limitation is that the "hit boxes" of buttons are not clipped by mask
  objects, so in some cases it may be possible to click on a button that
  cannot be seen, or a button that is visible may not be clicked, because
  it is blocked by an invisible button in front of it. Dropdown menus
  often exhibit this limitation.

o The swf library now supports sound envelopes, allowing the volume of a
  sound to be varied as it is played. This allows sounds to be faded in or
  out, as well as supporting other effects such as allowing a sound to be
  moved back and forth between the left and right audio channels.

Improvements made:

o Optimized the sound mixer code to make it a little faster.

o A few other optimizations were made, to slightly speed up the loading and
  playing of animations.

o The FlashPlayer source code received some improvements designed to make
  it easier to port FlashPlayer to other platforms.

Bugs fixed:

o Flash 8 and newer animations may make use of a new type of font
  definition that the swf library doesn't know how to read. This would
  cause Enforcer hits when the animation attempted to display text in one
  of these fonts. Such text is now safely ignored.

o The FlashPlayer icon distributed with version 1.2 was missing the new
  v. 1.2 tooltypes (they were present in the def_swf icon).


@{b}Version 1.2 27-Nov-05 (posted to Aminet 07-Dec-05)@{ub}

An update to add some new features, to optimize performance a bit, and to
fix quite a number of bugs in the swf library that prevented some (often
questionably written) animations from playing correctly.

Features added:

o Streaming sound is now decoded and played. No attempt is made to skip
  frames of the animation in order to keep up with the sound, so dropouts
  will occur if the animation cannot be drawn fast enough. This is usually
  the case, even with a 68060, so streaming sound may be disabled.

  All sound compression formats except the proprietary Nellymoser format
  are accepted in a sound stream, but so far only the MP3 format has been
  tested, as I have been unable to find streaming sound in any other
  format.

o Sound output is now in stereo (except at the low quality setting). Note
  that this requires twice as many sound samples to be processed, even for
  mono sounds, and so will likely require larger sound buffers to avoid
  dropouts. Because of this, the default sound buffer size has been in-
  creased to 96K.

o The swf library used by FlashPlayer now recognizes all actions and tags
  found in Flash files up through version 7. Of course, it still doesn't
  understand most of the newer ones, but it will list them when an ani-
  mation is loaded with the output set to verbose. Actions and tags that
  are unsupported by FlashPlayer are listed as such.

  FlashPlayer still sometimes reports unknown tags. These are either pro-
  prietary tags inserted by flash authoring tools, or tags that are un-
  documented by Adobe.

Improvements made:

o Added a @{"Settings" link "Control" 50} menu, which enables or disables the playing of streaming
  sound, and automatic looping of the animation.

o Rearranged some of the items in the Control menu, to more easily perform
  the @{"Stop-Step-Continue" link "Miscellany" 34} command sequence that helps FlashPlayer bypass
  some flash animation scripts.

o FlashPlayer will now attempt to play an animation even if the end is
  missing. Previously, such animations were rejected as being corrupt
  (which technically they are). This matches the behavior of the official
  Adobe player in allowing as much of such an animation as possible to be
  viewed.

o Made a number of miscellaneous tweaks to the swf library to slightly
  speed up the decoding and presentation of animations.

o Switched to version 0.15.1b of the MAD MPEG decoder library. The new
  version is faster at decoding MP3 sounds and is a little smaller. Using
  the current library version also makes it easier for others to compile
  FlashPlayer, since the library source code is readily available.

o Switched to version 1.2.3 of the zlib decompression library. The new
  version is faster and a bit smaller. Using the current library version
  also makes it easier for others to compile FlashPlayer, since the library
  source code is readily available.

Bugs fixed:

o Fixed a documentation bug: Tooltypes in an animation's icon will override
  command line arguments, not the other way around, as was mistakenly
  stated.

o FlashPlayer still sometimes incorrectly reported an out-of-memory problem
  as being a corrupt movie problem.

o "Sprites", or small animations nested within the main animation, tended
  to play correctly only once. If they were reused within the main anima-
  tion, or if the animation was rewound and played again, the sprites would
  not play a second time. Most sprites now play correctly, no matter how
  many times they're played.

o Animated button images would also tend to play correctly only the first
  time; thereafter they would display only the final image of the ani-
  mation. This has now been fixed, though the current fix goes a bit over-
  board, sometimes resetting the animation when it really shouldn't. Fixing
  this will require more effort, and is being postponed to a future version
  of FlashPlayer.

o When decoding MP3 sounds the swf library now skips the short silence that
  precedes many sounds. This is mainly audible when playing looping sounds;
  there is no longer a brief gap between loops.

o The last frame of MP3 sounds is now decoded- previously it was lost,
  though this was seldom audible.

o Eight bit sound samples are stored in SWF files in unsigned format, but
  AHI wants them signed. They are now converted to signed format when
  loaded.

o The swf library can now handle embedded JPEG images whose decoding tables
  are not stored separately, the way most are. This fixes the occasional
  animation that generated an "Improper call to JPEG library in state 202"
  error.

o The "hit box" for buttons is now clipped to the left and right edges of
  the FlashPlayer window. Scrolling the animation left or right (or the
  occasional broken animation) will no longer cause the hit boxes to spill
  out of the window.

o The swf library now always responds correctly when the mouse moves from
  a button to an immediately adjacent one. Previously the second button
  might not respond to the mouse.

o The swf library now correctly recognizes the outline of a button that has
  a hole or notch cut in it. Previously it would think that the hole or
  notch was part of the button, sometimes causing the wrong button to be
  selected.

o The swf library could sometimes draw the objects that make up a button
  image in the wrong order, causing the image to be incorrect (typically
  when the mouse moved over the button). This has been fixed.

o The swf library can now handle objects that are added to the display
  without proper sizing and location information. Previously this would
  cause Enforcer hits.

o Fixed an obscure bug in the swf library that caused complex actions
  within an animation to sometimes require several frames to execute,
  instead of executing in a single frame as intended. This was most fre-
  quently visible as an object within an animation disappearing for a frame
  or two, and then reappearing.

o The swf library now does a better job of handling complex button images;
  previously some parts of a complex button image might not have been dis-
  played.

o The swf library now correctly recognizes negative offsets when position-
  ing text; previously it would think the offset was a very large positive
  one, placing the text at a non-visible location.

o The swf library now correctly works with some animations that try to
  reference objects that haven't been drawn yet.

o Fixed a couple more cases where the swf library's attempts to execute a
  list of actions, while ignoring the script actions that it doesn't under-
  stand, could inadvertantly cause an infinite loop that crashed the player
  and/or the OS.

o Under certain conditions the swf libary might think that the last frame
  of an animation wasn't present, and so would refuse to play it. This is
  no longer the case.


@{b}Version 1.1 25-Dec-04 (posted to Aminet 27-Feb-05)@{ub}

An update to add some new features (allowing it to play, or more properly
play, many animations that version 1.0 could not), to make a few improve-
ments to the user interface, and to fix a few bugs.

Features added:

o Recognizes and loads compressed flash files ('CWS' file type).

o Implements much (but not all) of the "set target" and "goto label"
  functionality of the flash file format, which allows one button or
  portion of a flash animation to affect another.

  What effect this improvement will have depends on the animation. Some
  don't use this feature, and so will not benefit. But for those that do,
  it will allow the viewing of many effects (and some entire animations)
  that were formerly invisible.

o Support for looping (repeatedly playing) sounds, and using in- and out-
  points to play subsections of a sound.

o WIDTH and HEIGHT settings, which allow the dimensions of the player
  window to be precisely set in screen pixels. Primarily added in
  support of the future use of FlashPlayer as a browser plugin.

o A SOUNDBUF setting, which allows the size of the sound buffers to be
  optimized for a particular combination of animation and playback system.
  This is especially significant when playing looping sounds.

o More efficient use of double-buffering in the sound playing code,
  allowing for the use of smaller sound buffers for any given animation.

o A close box for the progress indicator that appears when an animation is
  loading; click it to cancel the animation (this will happen the next time
  the indicator is updated).

Features removed:

o Support for the FPU-optional version of FlashPlayer has been dropped.
  It takes a good deal of time to recompile all of the support libraries
  (MAD, JPEG, etc.) to work with the Amiga IEEE math libraries for every
  new release of FlashPlayer, and it seems unlikely that anyone would have
  enough patience to view an animation rendered using software floating-
  point arithmetic.

Improvements made:

o When FlashPlayer is going to open its window on a public screen, the
  progress indicator that's displayed while the animation is loading will
  open on the same screen, instead of on the Workbench.

Bugs fixed:

o When there was an error loading a flash animation, the "out of memory"
  and "corrupt file" error messages were swapped, thus incorrectly
  reporting the cause of the error.

o The diagnostic window now closes when the main FlashPlayer window is
  closed- allowing it to remain open until closed manually caused a memory
  leak of about 20K bytes every time FlashPlayer was run, even if the
  diagnostic window never opened.

o Some errors in the swf library's implementation of the various internal
  animation control actions like "play" and "advance to next frame" were
  corrected, to make the library work more like the official Adobe player.

  Note that in some cases this may cause FlashPlayer 1.1 to not be able to
  play some portion of an animation that the previous version could play.
  That's because that animation really requires scripting to play properly,
  and without scripting support, FlashPlayer 1.0 could play it only because
  it implemented the control actions incorrectly.

o Under certain rare conditions, the fact that the swf library ignored
  actions (such as scripts) that it didn't understand could cause an
  infinite loop when playing an animation, causing FlashPlayer - and often
  the operating system - to crash. The swf library now stops processing a
  list of actions when it encounters ones that might cause this problem.

  As a side effect of this change, FlashPlayer 1.1 is now able to play some
  animations correctly that the previous version could not, but also in
  some cases is unable to play animations that the previous version could.

o Removed a debugging remnant from the source code that, despite being
  perfectly legal under the Amiga OS, caused problems when porting the
  program to MorphOS.


@{b}Version 1.0 24-Jan-04 (posted to Aminet 03-Mar-04)@{ub}

The initial release of FlashPlayer.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Installation - How to install FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

Installation of FlashPlayer is fairly simple, so no install script is
provided. Start by dragging the drawer containing the program wherever you
want it. If you've already got the proper version of guigfx.library and
render.library installed, that's it- you're done (unless you want to set up
a default icon, as described below).

If you don't have these two libraries installed, you'll need to install the
appropriate version for your processor from the Libraries drawer inside the
FlashPlayer drawer. The libraries can be installed either into the
FlashPlayer drawer itself, or into LIBS:.

 CPU    guigfx.library        render.library
 -----  --------------------  --------------------
 68020  guigfx.library_FPU    render.library
 68030  guigfx.library_FPU    render.library
 68040  guigfx.library_68040  render.library_68040
 68060  guigfx.library_68060  render.library_68060

Whichever version of the libraries you choose, they must be renamed to
simply @{i}guigfx.library@{ui} and @{i}render.library@{ui}. Once installed, the Libraries
drawer may be deleted to save space.

FlashPlayer does not require any special configuration of AHI or
openurl.library; if you've already got these installed, FlashPlayer will
use them. FlashPlayer will run without AHI (it just won't be able to play
sounds) and without openurl.library (it just won't be able to send URLs to
your browser).

If you've got OS 3.5 or better, you might want to set DefIcons up to
recognize SWF files and display the default icon supplied with FlashPlayer.
This will allow Workbench to play any flash file, even if the file doesn't
have an icon of its own.

To do this, copy the default icon (def_swf.info) into the default icons
drawer (Sys:Prefs/Sys). Adjust the default tool in the icon to include the
path to where you've installed FlashPlayer. Now run the DefIcons
preferences program, and add an entry for 'swf' (I put mine under the
macroclass 'video'). Set the actions to '@{i}MATCH 0 "FWS" Case sensitive@{ui}
@{i}MATCH 0 "CWS" Case sensitive OR PATTERN #?.swf@{ui}'.

@endnode

@node "Workbench" "Workbench Operation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Workbench Operation - How to run FlashPlayer from the Workbench@{ub}@{fg text}

As with any Workbench program, there are a number of ways of running
FlashPlayer from the Workbench, differing mainly in how the file to be
opened is specified:

o Double-click its icon. A file requester will be opened to get the name of
  an animation to present.

o Double-click a project icon (including a default icon) that has
  FlashPlayer as its default tool. FlashPlayer will play the selected
  animation.

o Single-click a project icon, then hold down the shift key and double-
  click the FlashPlayer icon. FlashPlayer will play the selected animation.

o Single-click a project icon (including a default icon) that has
  FlashPlayer as its default tool, then select 'Open' from the Workbench's
  'Icons' menu (does anybody actually do this?). FlashPlayer will play the
  selected animation.

o If FlashPlayer is already running on the Workbench screen, an icon may be
  dragged onto its window to cause that animation to be played.

Note that FlashPlayer will only play one animation at a time, so selecting
multiple files by shift-clicking them will cause only the first to be
played. The options that FlashPlayer uses to control the presentation of
the selected animation are the same as those used when the program is run
from the shell. To avoid duplication, these options are explained under
@{"Options" link "Options" 0}.

When run from the Workbench, FlashPlayer employs a hierarchical method of
specifying the options that will control the program, with the goal of
allowing the user to override the program's built-in defaults with their
own preferences, but allowing those preferences to in turn be overridden by
special settings for a particular animation. The sequence that FlashPlayer
uses for setting the options is as follows:

1. First, FlashPlayer looks at the icon for the animation to be played, if
   one can be found (a default icon will be used if available and if no
   real icon is present). Any options set here will override any other
   options.

2. For any option not set by the animation's icon, FlashPlayer will read
   the tooltypes of its own icon. These options will override the program's
   built-in defaults.

3. For any option not overridden by one of the above methods, FlashPlayer
   will use its built-in default setting.

While this hierarchical scheme is flexible, it may also be confusing to
understand. The best way of understanding it is likely to be to play with
it some, but perhaps it will also help to look at it from a different
angle.

1. FlashPlayer starts out with a set of built-in defaults for all of its
   options.

2. It then reads any options set in its own icon. These are used to
   override the defaults.

3. Finally, it reads any options set in the icon of the animation to be
   played. These are used to override any options set so far.

Normally, you will use the FlashPlayer icon to set your standard set of
options, which will be used for all animations played. If any of the
animations needs special settings (a particular screen mode or sound buffer
size, for instance), that option may be set in the animation's icon.

@endnode

@node "Shell" "Shell Operation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Shell Operation - How to run FlashPlayer from the shell@{ub}@{fg text}

To run FlashPlayer from the shell or CLI, just type its name (optionally
preceeded by 'Run', to detach it from the shell), followed by the name of
the file to be played, optionally followed by additional arguments to
specify its mode of operation:

 [Run] FlashPlayer <FileName.swf> [Options]

The template for the program, which may be displayed by typing 'FlashPlayer
?', is:

 FILE,SCREEN/K,SCALE/K/N,WIDTH/K/N,HEIGHT/K/N,QUALITY/K,SOUND/K,
 SOUNDBUF/K/N,URL/K,LOOP/K,OUTPUT/K

o FILE
  The name of the flash file to be played. If it contains spaces, it must
  be surrounded by quotes. The 'FILE' keyword is optional. FlashPlayer will
  only play one file at a time, so if multiple files are given, only the
  first will be played. For this reason, FlashPlayer does not support
  wildcards in the file name. If no name is given, a file requester will be
  opened.

The remainder of the options are the same as the tooltypes used when the
program is run from the Workbench. To avoid duplication, these options are
explained under @{"Options" link "Options" 0}.

When run from the shell, FlashPlayer employs a hierarchical method of
specifying the options that will control the program, with the goal of
allowing the user to override the program's built-in defaults with their
own preferences, but allowing those preferences to in turn be overridden by
special settings for a particular animation. The sequence that FlashPlayer
uses for setting the options is as follows:

1. First, FlashPlayer looks at the icon for the animation to be played, if
   one can be found (a default icon will be used if available and if no
   real icon is present). Any options set here will override any other
   options.

2. For any option not set by the animation's icon, FlashPlayer will read
   the command line options.

3. For any option not set by the command line or via the animation's icon,
   FlashPlayer will read the tooltypes of its own icon. These options will
   override the program's built-in defaults.

4. For any option not overridden by one of the above methods, FlashPlayer
   will use its built-in default setting.

While this hierarchical scheme is flexible, it may also be confusing to
understand. The best way of understanding it is likely to be to play with
it some, but perhaps it will also help to look at it from a different
angle.

1. FlashPlayer starts out with a set of built-in defaults for all of its
   options.

2. It then reads any options set in its own icon. These are used to
   override the defaults.

3. It next reads the command line arguments. These are used to override
   any options set so far.

4. Finally, it looks at any options set in the icon of the animation to be
   played. These are used to override any options set previously.

Normally, you will use the FlashPlayer icon to set your standard set of
options, which will be used for all animations played. If any of the
animations needs special settings (a particular scale factor or sound
buffer size, for instance), that option may be set in the animation's icon.
Finally, the command-line arguments may be used to make any special
adjustments, such as turning on diagnostic output while debugging a
particular animation.

@endnode

@node "Options" "Options"

@{b}@{fg shine}Options - Options to configure FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

Whether run from the @{"shell" link "Shell" 0} or from the @{"Workbench" link "Workbench" 0}, FlashPlayer uses the
same options to configure its operation. When specified from the shell's
command line, the option's keyword is given, followed by the setting for
that option (for example, SOUND NO). When specified via an icon's
tooltypes, the option's keyword is given, followed (with no spaces) by an
equals sign, followed (again, no spaces) by the option's setting (for
example, SOUND=NO). Although the keywords and options are shown in upper
case, they are in fact not case sensitive.

o @{b}SCREEN <Screen Name>@{ub}
  This keyword specifies the name of a screen to be used to present the
  animation. The screen name may be either that of a public screen, or the
  name of a screen mode, exactly as shown in the list in the Workbench's
  ScreenMode preferences window. When specified via the shell, screen names
  with spaces in them must be surrounded by quotes. This is not necessary
  if specifying the screen name in a tooltype. If no screen is specified or
  if FlashPlayer is unable to open on the specified screen, it will fall
  back to the Workbench screen.

  An example of a public screen name would be "IBrowse Screen", while an
  example of a screen mode name would be "PicassoII:800x600 16bit PC".
  (Note that the screen mode names in the ScreenMode preferences program
  are sometimes truncated due to being too long to fit in the list; if
  FlashPlayer seems to be ignoring your screen mode, this may be what's
  happening. Try another screen mode editor such as MUI's PSI.)

o @{b}SCALE <Percent>@{ub}
  The scale of the FlashPlayer window, in percent of normal. A scale of 100
  (the default if no scale is specified, or if set to zero) causes the
  animation to be presented at its intended size. Lower numbers will make
  the animation smaller, while larger numbers will make it bigger. When
  using scaling, the aspect ratio of the FlashPlayer window will match that
  of the animation. SCALE interacts with the WIDTH and HEIGHT settings, as
  described below.

  Scaling is most useful for speeding up a large animation by reducing its
  size (especially helpful when playing streaming sound). But because flash
  animations mostly use vector graphics, enlarging an animation will allow
  it to be seen in more detail, without blockiness (an exception to this
  would be bitmapped images used within the animation).

  Note that the swf library's presentation engine does not support resizing
  an animation on the fly, so FlashPlayer's window is not resizable while
  an animation is playing.

o @{b}WIDTH <Pixels>@{ub}
  The internal width of the FlashPlayer window to be used in playing the
  animation, in screen pixels. The actual width of the window will be
  greater, due to its borders. The default is zero, which maintains the
  intended width of the animation. WIDTH interacts with the SCALE and
  HEIGHT settings, as described below.

o @{b}HEIGHT <Pixels>@{ub}
  The internal height of the FlashPlayer window to be used in playing the
  animation, in screen pixels. The actual height of the window will be
  greater, due to its borders. The default is zero, which maintains the
  intended height of the animation. HEIGHT interacts with the SCALE and
  WIDTH settings, as described below.

  @{b}Interaction between SCALE, WIDTH, and HEIGHT@{ub}

  These three settings all combine to control the size of the FlashPlayer
  window, and indirectly the size at which the flash animation will be
  played. Indirectly, because the original aspect ratio of the animation
  will always be maintained, regardless of the size of the player window.

  SCALE adjusts the size of the window proportionally to that of the
  animation, such that the animation will always completely fill the
  window.

  WIDTH and HEIGHT force the width and height of the window, respectively,
  to the specified dimension. Because the original aspect ratio of the
  animation is maintained, it may not always completely fill the resulting
  window. For that reason, SCALE is preferred when it is desired to change
  the size of the animation. The WIDTH and HEIGHT settings are provided
  for special cases where the animation size needs to be tightly
  controlled.

  When the three settings are given simultaneously, FlashPlayer first
  applies the SCALE setting, using it to determine the width and height of
  the player window. The WIDTH and/or HEIGHT settings are applied after the
  scaling, further modifying the dimensions (and where a setting of zero
  keeps the dimension determined by SCALE, not the original dimension of
  the animation).

  FlashPlayer will limit the minimum and maximum dimensions of the
  window to safe values, regardless of the dimensions set with SCALE,
  WIDTH, and HEIGHT. Further, it will not allow the size of the window to
  exceed the size of the screen. Because of this, the ultimate size of the
  window may not be exactly what you specified, if you asked for something
  too extreme.

o @{b}QUALITY <LOW or MEDIUM or HIGH>@{ub}
  The presentation quality to be used for playing the animation. In
  general, the higher the presentation quality, the slower the animation
  will play, and the more memory it will use. Only the first letter of the
  quality setting is read, so LOW may be abbreviated as LO or L; the same
  applies to the other settings.

  Adjusting the quality currently has the following effect:

  LOW quality uses no dithering on colormapped screens (no effect on high-
      or true-color graphics card screens), and plays mono sounds at
      11 KHz.

  MEDIUM quality uses EDD dithering on colormapped screens (no effect on
      high- or true-color graphics card screens), and plays stereo sounds
      at 11 KHz.

  HIGH quality uses Floyd-Steinberg dithering on colormapped screens (no
      effect on high- or true-color graphics card screens), and plays
      stereo sounds at 22 KHz.

  The default is MEDIUM quality.

o @{b}SOUND <YES or XSTREAM or NO>@{ub}
  Enable (YES) or disable (NO) the playing of sounds contained within an
  animation. Because FlashPlayer usually can't play streaming sound fast
  enough to avoid dropouts, XSTREAM may be used to disable only streaming
  sound, while enabling all other sound. Only the first letter of the
  setting is read, so YES may be abbreviated as Y, XSTREAM may be
  abbreviated as X, and NO may be abbreviated as N.

  Disabling streaming sound can save quite a bit of memory, as there is no
  need to store the streaming sound data in memory. Disabling sound
  completely saves even more memory, by eliminating the need for sound
  buffers, and the need to load AHI. The default setting is YES unless AHI
  cannot be opened, in which case sound will be disabled.

  Playing of streaming sound may still be disabled using the @{"Settings" link "Control" 50} menu,
  even if SOUND is set to YES. However, because setting SOUND to XSTREAM
  prevents the decoding of streaming sound data, the Settings menu cannot
  override XSTREAM and cause streaming sound to be played.

o @{b}SOUNDBUF <KBytes>@{ub}
  Sets the size of the sound buffers used by FlashPlayer, in kbytes. The
  default if not otherwise set (or if set to zero) is 96 kB. The maximum
  is 255 kB. FlashPlayer uses double-buffering for improved sound quality,
  so there will be two buffers of this size allocated. The size of the
  buffers is automatically doubled when playing at HIGH quality, to
  accommodate the faster sample rate, and is automatically halved when
  playing at LOW quality, because mono sound requires fewer samples.

  Making the buffers smaller uses less memory, and allows more responsive
  sound (that is, the sound is better synchronized to an action, such as a
  button press, that triggered it). However, small buffers are also more
  prone to dropouts as the frame rate of the animation slows due to a large
  or complex animation, or a slow system.

  The default buffer size of 96 kB is a safe compromise for most systems
  and most animations, but for best sound reproduction you may wish to
  experiment to determine the optimum buffer size for your system, and
  potentially for each different animation. Generally, the best size for
  the buffer is the smallest that avoids dropouts.

o @{b}URL <YES or NO>@{ub}
  Enable (YES) or disable (NO) the the sending of URLs found in the
  animation to a web browser via openurl.library. This includes sending of
  URLs of animations that are intended to be shown as part of the current
  animation (currently these are shown in a separate FlashPlayer window).
  Only the first letter of the yes/no setting is read, so YES may be
  abbreviated as Y and NO may be abbreviated as N.

  The default is for "URL visiting" to be disabled; this will also happen
  if openurl.library cannot be opened. Setting the diagnostic level to
  NORMAL or VERBOSE causes URLs to be listed whether or not "URL visiting"
  is enabled; this may be used to see where the browser would be directed
  without actually going there.

  When told to load a second animation as part of the one that's currently
  playing, FlashPlayer will attempt to load the animation from the local
  drive (the same folder where the currently-playing animation is located)
  before attempting to load the animation via the browser. This will occur
  even if "URL visiting" is disabled.

o @{b}LOOP <YES or NO>@{ub}
  Enable (YES) or disable (NO) automatic looping of animations when they
  reach their end. Only the first letter of the yes/no setting is read, so
  YES may be abbreviated as Y and NO may be abbreviated as N.

  The default is for looping to be enabled. Looping may be enabled or dis-
  abled using the @{"Settings" link "Control" 50} menu, regardless of the setting of LOOP.

o @{b}OUTPUT <NORMAL or QUIET or VERBOSE>@{ub}
  Set the level of diagnostic output presented by FlashPlayer as it runs.
  Only the first letter of the diagnostic setting is read, so NORMAL may be
  abbreviated as NORM or N; the same applies to the other settings.

  When QUIET is specified, FlashPlayer will generate no diagnostic output,
  even when an error occurs (note that an error requester may still be
  displayed; this setting only applies to output to the diagnostic console
  window). When NORMAL is specified, only errors (and URLs to be visited)
  are output.

  When VERBOSE is specified, the program outputs various information (and
  quite a lot of it) on the file decoding and presentation process, as well
  as errors and URLs to be visited. Displaying all this information can
  make loading an animation rather slow. There's no way to turn verbose
  output off once it's started, but the display can be sped up by making
  the diagnostic window small, or even hiding it behind another window. The
  animation can also be cancelled using the close box on the progress
  indicator.

@endnode

@node "Control" "Control"

@{b}@{fg shine}Control - How to use FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

FlashPlayer is controlled by a couple of menus, and a number of keyboard
commands. The mouse may also interact with many animations.

@{b}Menus@{ub}

@{i}Project Menu @{ui}

o Open (Right-Amiga O)
  Close the current animation, and bring up a file requester to get the
  name of another animation to play. Canceling the requester will quit
  FlashPlayer.

o Movie Info (Right-Amiga I)
  Bring up a requester with information on the animation currently playing
  (playing will stop while the requester is open).

  @{i}Movie Name:@{ui} The name of the animation being played.
  @{i}Flash Format Version:@{ui} The version of the flash file.
  @{i}Number of Frames:@{ui} The number of individual frames in the animation.
  @{i}Frame Rate:@{ui} The intended frame rate of the animation.
  @{i}Frame Size:@{ui} The intended frame size of the animation.

o About (Right-Amiga ?)
  Display the version of FlashPlayer, as well as credits for the program
  and the libraries it uses. Playing will stop while the requester is
  open.

o Quit (Right-Amiga Q)
  Like it says.

@{i}Control Menu @{ui}

Note that these controls apply only to the main animation; they will not
affect any animations that the main animation may have loaded itself.

o Stop (Right-Amiga X)
  Stop playing the animation.

o Rewind (Right-Amiga R)
  Rewind the animation to the beginning.

o Step (Right-Amiga S)
  Single-step to the next frame of the animation.

o Continue (Right-Amiga C)
  Resume playing the animation.

@{i}Settings Menu @{ui}

o Loop Movie (Right-Amiga L)
  Enable or disable looping of the animation. If enabled (a checkmark will
  appear), the animation will automatically restart when it reaches the
  end. Some animations are not designed to loop, and will not respond to
  this setting. Some animations always loop, regardless of this setting.

o Streaming Sound (Right-Amiga E)
  Enable or disable the playing of streaming sound. Non-streaming sound is
  not affected. If streaming sound has been disabled by the @{"SOUND=XSTREAM" link "Options" 118}
  command line option or tooltype, this setting will have no effect.

@{b}Keyboard Commands@{ub}

o Arrow keys, Tab key, Return and Enter keys
  These keys are passed on to the animation that is being played. If the
  animation has buttons that may be operated, the tab key and the arrow
  keys will move among them, with the currently-selected button being high-
  lighted. Pressing the Return or Enter keys will operate the selected
  button, as if it had been clicked on by the mouse. If the animation has
  no buttons, these keys will do nothing.

o Keypad arrow keys
  Scroll the flash animation relative to the FlashPlayer window. This is
  typically done when the animation has been enlarged by zooming in on
  it, but may be done even if this is not the case.

o Keypad '5' key
  Move the animation back to its standard position, if it's been scrolled
  with the keypad arrow keys.

o Keypad PgUp and PgDn keys
  Enlarge the animation by zooming in on it (PgUp), or reduce it by zooming
  out (PgDn). The swf presentation engine supports zoom factors of 1, 2,
  and 3; attempting to zoom beyond this has no effect.

o Keypad Home key
  Restore the zoom factor to normal (1).

@{b}Mouse Control@{ub}

Many flash animations are interactive, and may be controlled with the
mouse. When moving the mouse over a "button" or clickable area on the
animation, the mouse pointer will change to a pointing hand. Clicking the
mouse when this happens will trigger an event within the animation, causing
it to take some action.

Note that many flash animations use the scripting features of flash 4 and
up to respond to mouse activity, and since FlashPlayer does not support
scripting, the animation will often not respond to a mouse click, even
though the pointing-hand pointer is present.

@{b}FlashPlayer Window@{ub}

When running on the Workbench screen, FlashPlayer sets itself up as an
AppWindow, which means that dragging an icon onto the FlashPlayer window
will tell it to load and play that file. Of course, if the file is not a
flash animation or a flash EXE this will not succeed.

@{b}Diagnostic Output Window@{ub}

When FlashPlayer generates diagnostic output, it does so to a console
window separate from the FlashPlayer window. The console window always
opens on the Workbench screen, even if FlashPlayer is running on some other
screen. The console window opens only when needed, so it will not open if
there is no output to display, even if diagnostic output has been enabled.
The window may be closed using its close box at any time, even while
FlashPlayer is still running; if need be, another window will be opened for
displaying further output. The window will automatically be closed when
FlashPlayer is quit.

@endnode

@node "Miscellany" "Miscellany"

@{b}@{fg shine}Miscellany - Odds and ends regarding FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

As I did not write the code that provides the bulk of FlashPlayer's
functionality, I cannot speak much as to its robustness. The jpeg, zlib,
and MAD libraries are well used, even in the PC/Unix world, and so are
presumably pretty solid. The swf library is less well used, as Adobe
supplies flash players for most platforms. In my testing the swf library
has proven to be solid when playing valid swf files. It may not be able to
properly present everything in the file, but it doesn't crash or otherwise
misbehave. I have not attempted to test it with improperly formatted files
to see how it handles these, nor have I tested it under low memory
conditions.

I have only a single system on which to develop and test FlashPlayer (an
Amiga 3000 desktop with a Cyberstorm MkIII 50 MHz 68060 and 32 + 14 + 2 MB
of RAM, running OS 3.9 or OS 3.1, with a Picasso II running Picasso 96, and
native Amiga sound running AHI 6). The use of libraries such as guigfx and
AHI to handle graphical and sound output should minimize the possibility of
problems on other systems, but something still could go wrong.

---

If FlashPlayer doesn't seem to be playing an animation properly, it
probably isn't. As mentioned elsewhere, the swf library that FlashPlayer
uses @{"does not support all flash features" link "Introduction" 97}, even in animations that don't use
scripting. Similar to the way Amiga web browsers compare with their PC
brethren, FlashPlayer works well enough to give you the gist of most
animations that don't require advanced features, but they will often look
or sound different than when they're played on a PC using Adobe's flash
player.

---

While testing FlashPlayer I have discovered that it is sometimes possible
to view portions of flash animations that normally don't run due to the
lack of scripting support. Typically these animations will display a home
image, and then will wait for the user to trigger a script with the mouse
before they go on.

By using the 'Step' menu option it is sometimes possible to force the
animation to bypass the wait and play the portion of the animation that is
normally activated by the script. When confronted with such an animation,
try selecting 'Step', then 'Continue'. It may be necessary to try
variations such as 'Step', 'Step', 'Continue'. Sometimes it helps to select
'Stop' first, even though the animation doesn't appear to be doing
anything. By employing this technique I have been able to play animations
that were unplayable otherwise.

Of course, this doesn't always work. Sometimes you just end up at a
different image that doesn't do anything (though you can always try the
same technique again). And some animations simply aren't structured in a
way that responds to this technique.

Also note that this technique only works on the main animation being
viewed. If the main animation has loaded another animation ("picture in
picture" mode), it is not possible to send commands to that animation.

@endnode

@node "Future" "The Future"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Future - What's ahead for FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

My plan had been that FlashPlayer 1.4 would be the last 1.x version, and
that the next release would be v. 2.0. I planned to make the standalone
version of FlashPlayer into a "shell" that used the new plugin to do most
of the work. That way, I wouldn't need to duplicate the swf library into
both the plugin and the standalone. But the IBrowse plugin interface turned
out to use MUI in a way that would have been difficult to duplicate for a
non-MUI application. So instead, I have continued on the 1.x path, and the
plugin and the standalone player will continue to be separate projects.

I have a full-time job and family commitments, and so don't have a lot of
time to devote to projects such as FlashPlayer. Because of this, it tends
to be quite a while between updates to the program (historically, almost a
year). Still, I hope to keep playing with the @{"swf library" link "Credits" 23}, fixing
shortcomings and adding new features to better enable it to present flash
animations. The GUI could also get some tweaks to make it more powerful and
easier to use.

Beyond that lies the realm of more extensive changes to the swf library.
The most called-for change would be the addition of scripting support, to
handle the large number of animations that rely on this. The handling of
Flash 4 scripting seems feasible- I intend to look into the possibility of
adding it to a future version of FlashPlayer, but make no promises. Flash 5
scripting is much more complicated, and it seems unlikely at this point
that it will ever become a part of FlashPlayer. The script format has
changed again as of Flash 9, so a full-featured player now needs to support
three scripting languages- even more unlikely for FlashPlayer.

Naturally, as an open-source project, the code to FlashPlayer is available
to anyone who wants to enhance it or extend it in new directions, just as I
have done with the original swf library.

@{b}Gnash@{ub}

Gnash @{b}(www.gnash.org)@{ub} is the most popular and most advanced of the open
source flash players. Among other things, it supports most of the Flash 5
script language (and is making progress on the Flash 9 version), and it can
play streaming video from web sites like YouTube. I'm sometimes asked if it
makes sense to continue to develop FlashPlayer, rather than working towards
porting Gnash to the Amiga.

The problem with porting Gnash is that it depends on a bunch of other
libraries for many of its features, and few of them are available for the
Amiga. So in order to port Gnash itself, I'd have to first port all these
other libraries (which may in turn depend on yet other libraries), making
it into a very large project.

Gnash is also being developed on GHz-class PCs, and so is oriented more
towards capability and reduced development time than efficiency. As such,
its performance would be poor on the Amiga platform, particularly on 68K
Amigas.

So while it would be nice to have the capabilities of Gnash available on
the Amiga, it isn't currently practical. But while I can't just port Gnash
to the Amiga, I can always borrow some code - and some knowledge - from it.

@endnode
